top.value: The project aimed to increase capacity of parties to the Convention on Biological                Diversity (CBD) to operationalize the Nagoya Protocol in a country-tailored manner that effectively                contributes to sustainable development, poverty reduction and environmental sustainability goals.

To identify, train and support national legal advisors that can actively advance                the long-term process of developing, implementing and revising Access and Benefit Sharing (ABS)                regulatory frameworks in their countries.

Government officials working in the ministries or agencies responsible for                legislative and regulatory responses to non-communicable diseases (NCDs), academic institutions,                patients groups, childrens rights organisations, womens organisations, youth                groups, labor groups, and faith communities, consumer organisations, and civil society organizations                that are engaged in project activities.
National lawyers and policymakers, CBD parties, stakeholders engaged in ABS                issues.
Proposed civil society organizations identified for support in each country; people                living with HIV and members of key affected populations.
The High Qualification Commission of Judges and the High Council of Justice Ethics                Commission

Direct beneficiaries: Experts drawn from representatives of the Member States of                the Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD), the African Union, the United Nations system and                other international organizations, think tanks, academia, civil society organizations, and the private                sector.
Indirect beneficiaries: Population of East Africa, particularly women and girls, and parties                to land conflicts.
1) To improve judicial capacity in economic laws. 2) To enhance entrepreneurs                ability, with a focus on women entrepreneurs, to access justice in related commercial matters.

1) To strengthen the capacity of government officials, regulators, policymakers,                research institutions and civil society to understand, develop and implement (as appropriate) regulatory                and fiscal measures that promote healthy diets and physical activity. 2) To strengthen national and                international collaboration amongst lawyers, regulatory bodies, policymakers, research institutions,                civil society actors and communities to support regulatory and fiscal environments that promote healthy                diets and physical activity. 3) To increase generation and use of relevant evidence and research from                different disciplines to develop and implement effective regulatory and fiscal measures to promote                healthy diets and physical activities.
